In Carcassonne centre itself you will find a maze of tiny streets, a beautiful square filled with pavement caf√©s, restaurants and shops - three times a week there is a fantastic market selling fresh French produce. Stroll around this extensive, quintessential French market, buy a delicious picnic, then take a walk through the narrow streets to the banks of the Aude river, where you can look up and marvel at the splendour of the ancient castle in front of you. On Bastille day (14th July), the castle is the backdrop for one of the largest firework displays in France.

Discover the magical atmosphere in Carcassonne at Christmas, an open-air ice rink in the square surrounded by a typically French Christmas market of little wooden chalets. At most times of year there is something going on here, whether it be a Spanish festival, street market or art exhibition, there really is something for everyone.

<strong><a href="http://www.carcassonne.org">www.carcassonne.org</a></strong>";s:9:"post_name";s:19:"carcassonne-la-cite";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"2";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2016-05-03 09:24:48";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2016-04-21 16:17:35";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2016-04-21 16:17:35";}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"280";s:10:"post_title";s:21:"Spain & Mediterranean";s:12:"post_content";s:930:"If you can drag yourself away from the pool and fancy a day lazing on a Mediterranean beach, then jump in the car and within an hour you could be sitting on one of many beautiful wide sandy beaches. Gruissan, with its little chalets on stilts also has a charming old town filled will seafood restaurants and pavement caf√©s, while a little further south near the Spanish border is Collioure, a picturesque old fishing port. The coastal town of S√®te famous for its oyster beds is a must to visit and during the summer months jousting tournaments are held there - on boats in the harbour. It's hilarious. The kids will love it.

